["English: from Middle English <i>clerk</i>, <i>clark</i> ‘clerk, cleric, writer’ (Old French <i>clerc</i>; see   Clerc  ). The original sense was ‘man in a religious order, cleric, clergyman’. As all writing and secretarial work in medieval Christian Europe was normally done by members of the clergy, the term <i>clerk</i> came to mean ‘scholar, secretary, recorder, or penman’ as well as ‘cleric’. As a surname, it was particularly common for one who had taken only minor holy orders. In medieval Christian Europe, clergy in minor orders were permitted to marry and so found families; thus the surname could become established.","Irish (Westmeath, Mayo): in Ireland the English surname was frequently adopted, partly by translation for <i>Ó Cléirigh</i>; see   Cleary  .","Americanized form of Dutch   De Klerk   or Flemish   De Clerck   or of variants of these names, and possibly also of French   Clerc  . Compare   Clerk   2 and   De Clark  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"John Clarke was born in 1514 as the son of Sir James Clarke. He had at least 2 sons with Margaret Walker. He died in 1598, at the age of 84."},"et":{"1514–1598":"1514–1598","1520–Male":"1520–Surnud","1522–Female":"1522–Surnud","1529–1590":"1529–1590","1531–1596":"1531–1596","1535–1596":"1535–1596","1537–1584":"1537–1584","1539–1614":"1539–1614","1541–Male":"1541–Surnud","1513–1566":"1513–1566","1532–1588":"1532–1588","1485–1554":"1485–1554","May 10 1588":"10. mai 1588","1590":"1590","1514":"1514","1513":"1513","1535":"1535","1566":"1566","1588":"1588","1522":"1522","1532":"1532","1598":"1598","1554":"1554","1531":"1531","1520":"1520